## Content Security Policy — Nonce-Based (Both Scripts and Styles)

`security_headers_middleware` generates a **per-request cryptographic nonce** stored in `request.state.csp_nonce`. Both `script-src` and `style-src` use this nonce — **neither uses `'unsafe-inline'`**.

```python
nonce = _secrets.token_urlsafe(16)
request.state.csp_nonce = nonce

csp_directives = [
    f"script-src 'self' 'nonce-{nonce}' ...",
    f"style-src  'self' 'nonce-{nonce}' https://fonts.googleapis.com ...",
    # NO 'unsafe-inline' in either directive
]
```

### Rules for new templates

1. **Every `<script>` block** must carry `nonce="{{ request.state.csp_nonce | default('') }}"`.
2. **Every `<style>` block** must carry `nonce="{{ request.state.csp_nonce | default('') }}"`.
3. **Never add `style="..."` HTML attributes.** Use CSS classes instead (see `app.css` utilities below). Inline `style=` attributes are blocked by CSP and violate rule #32 in `.cursorrules`.
4. **Dynamic CSS values** (e.g. widths set from data) must be set via JavaScript (`element.style.width = ...`) — JS-applied inline styles are not governed by `style-src` CSP.

### Global CSS utility classes (`ui/static/css/app.css`)

These replace the patterns that previously required inline `style=` attributes:

| Class | CSS | Replaces |
|-------|-----|---------|
| `.is-hidden` | `display: none` | `style="display: none"` |
| `.flex-1` | `flex: 1` | `style="flex: 1"` |
| `.cursor-pointer` | `cursor: pointer` | `style="cursor: pointer"` |
| `.text-accent` | `color: var(--accent-primary)` | `style="color: var(--accent-primary)"` |
| `.text-secondary` | `color: var(--text-secondary) !important` | `style="color: var(--text-secondary)"` |
| `.font-mono-inline` | `font-family: var(--font-mono)` | `style="font-family: var(--font-mono)"` |

**Important:** `.is-hidden` does **not** use `!important` — this is intentional. JavaScript can show hidden elements via `element.style.display = 'block'` (inline style overrides a non-`!important` class). Never change `.is-hidden` to add `!important`, and never use Bootstrap's `d-none` for elements that JS shows/hides via `.style.display`.

### CSS Specificity Conflict — Page `<style>` vs `.is-hidden`

When a page `<style>` block defines `display` on a single class (e.g. `.job-badge { display: inline-flex }`), it has **identical specificity** (one class = 0,1,0) to `.is-hidden { display: none }` in `app.css`. Because the page `<style>` is parsed after the linked stylesheet, it wins — `.is-hidden` is silently ignored for those elements and they are always visible.

**Fix:** Add a two-class rule in the **same page `<style>` block** to override at higher specificity (0,2,0):

```css
/* In the page <style> block, alongside the display-setting rule */
.job-badge { display: inline-flex; ... }
.job-badge.is-hidden { display: none; }  /* ← two classes; wins over both */
```

Apply this pattern whenever a page-level style sets `display` on a class that also needs to respect `.is-hidden` toggling.

